## Code Style (enforced on every Solidity file)

Match the documentation style of OpenZeppelin, Uniswap, and Solady. A
reviewer should understand every non-obvious decision from the NatSpec
alone.

- **No `//` or `///`.** All comments are `/* */` or NatSpec `/** */`. Never
  `///` triple-slash, even though NatSpec accepts it.
- **No em or en dashes.** U+2014 (EM DASH) and U+2013 (EN DASH) are banned
  everywhere. Use hyphen, colon, comma, parentheses, or rephrase.
- **File header** - open every `.sol` with:

  ```solidity
  /* SPDX-License-Identifier: MIT */
  pragma solidity ^0.8.28;

  /**
   * @file MyContract.sol
   * @description One-line purpose. Terse, factual.
   */
  ```

- **Section dividers** are asterisk-bordered box comments, one line each:

  ```solidity
  /*************** Internal ***************/
  /*************** Public Decryption - 3-Step Self-Relaying ***************/
  /*************** Storage Layout ***************/
  ```

  At least 10 leading and 10 trailing `*`, Title Case label.

- **Contract-level NatSpec** uses the full industry tag set:

  ```solidity
  /**
   * @title ConfidentialERC20
   * @author YourOrg
   * @notice Minimal confidential ERC-20 with encrypted balances.
   * @dev Balances are encrypted euint64 handles. Overflow wraps silently
   *      in FHE arithmetic; transfers route through FHE.le + FHE.select.
   * @custom:security-contact security@yourorg.example
   */
  contract ConfidentialERC20 is ZamaEthereumConfig { }
  ```

- **Function-level NatSpec** - every `external` / `public` function. Use:
  `@notice` (user-facing), `@dev` (invariants, preconditions, gas / HCU,
  design notes), `@param` (one per parameter), `@return` (one per
  returned value), `@inheritdoc ParentName` when implementing an interface
  (preferred over duplicating `@notice`).
- **NatSpec is Solidity-only.** The tags above (`@notice`, `@dev`,
  `@inheritdoc`, `@title`, `@custom:*`) are parsed by the Solidity
  compiler and tools like `solidity-docgen`. They are NOT valid JSDoc
  and must never appear in `.ts` / `.tsx` / `.js` / `.jsx` files - those
  use JSDoc (see `fhevm-frontend.mdc` / `fhevm-testing.mdc` for TS rules).
- **Inline comments** explain WHY, not WHAT. Spend them on FHE constraints:
  handle-order requirements, transient vs persistent ACL, `allowThis`
  lifecycle, overflow-wrap assumptions, power-of-2 random bounds.

Post-code style grep (zero matches required):

```
Comments: ^\s*//[^\*]|^\s*///
Glyphs:   [\x{2013}\x{2014}\x{1F680}\x{26A0}]
```

(Asterisk-box section dividers are NOT grepped - they are preferred.)

